This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society) because it examines the impact of clickbait headlines on readers' engagement with reliable health information, which is related to the social and ethical implications of technology. It could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) because the study involves testing readers' engagement with and perception about clickbait headlines, which is related to information retrieval and search engines. Additionally, cs.CL (Computation and Language) could be a possible sub-category because the study involves analyzing the language used in clickbait headlines and designing an automation system to generate them. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) are also possible sub-categories because the study involves testing readers' engagement with online content and designing an automation system to maximize user engagement.
